<DOCNO> AP891018-0001 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president bush on wednesday declared the 
earthquakeshattered san francisco bay region a major disaster 
area calling the devastation a matter of grave national 
concern and directing an initial 273 million to relief efforts 
bush said he wants to inspect the damage personally and 
officials said the trip west was likely friday or saturday 
i want the citizens of the san francisco bay area and its 
neighbors first to know that our hearts are with them as they face 
this terrible tragedy the president said 
words cant adequately convey our sentiments i know but i 
can say that we will take every step and make every effort to help 
the bay area in its hour of need 
stung by criticism of the governments response to hurricane 
hugo bush made a point of praising the federal emergency 
management agency which plays the lead role in federal disaster 
relief efforts 
i hope there will be less carping bush said i think they 
took a bad hit on that other one from some quarters he commented 
after an unscheduled moraleboosting visit to fema headquarters 
where relief efforts by 25 federal agencies were being planned and 
coordinated 
bush received a telephoned report from air force two carrying 
vice president dan quayle to washington from a tour of the damage 
quayle told reporters at andrews air force base near washington he 
stressed the importance of volunteer rescue efforts and 
preparation noting an august earthquake response drill held by 
state and federal agencies 
it could have been much worse if we had not had that 
preparation quayle said 
the vice president said he believed its under control and we 
are making progress there will be adequate personnel there 
are many volunteers federal funds will be forthcoming 
bush received messages of sympathy and offers of support from 
numerous world leaders including soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev who received us help after last decembers devastating 
earthquake in armenia 
if these countries can help we certainly welcome their 
assistance said white house press secretary marlin fitzwater 
bush said he wants to visit the devastated area but that there 
are certain security constraints connected with this job and the 
last thing we want to do is clutter things up but i do want to 
make a trip out there and i probably will 
the white house said the initial 273 million will come from 
unallocated money in a 11 billion appropriation approved earlier 
for hurricane hugo relief 
rep vic fazio dcalif chairman of the house appropriations 
subcommittee with jurisdiction over fema said members of congress 
were giving the agency high marks so far but it would need more 
money no question we would want to take funds out of existing 
programs we need the administrations cooperation to get that 
funding fazio said 
bushs earthquake disaster declaration authorizes the government 
to play a major role in relief and recovery efforts paying at 
least 75 percent of the cost of rebuilding bridges and other public 
facilities and providing lowcost loans for individuals and 
businesses 
even the internal revenue service got into the act announcing 
that it would waive penalties for taxpayers unable to file returns 
or make scheduled payments because of the earthquake 
the areas covered by bushs order include the city and county of 
san francisco and the counties of alameda monterey san benito 
san mateo santa clara and santa cruz 
bush during a meeting with elementary school principals from 
around the country singled out ray tolcacher superintendent of 
windsor union school district in san francisco 
we just hope that your kids and your schools and all the 
families are safe and sound bush said 
he said his administration is working closely with california 
state officials to provide assistance saying it is a matter of 
grave national concern 
within hours of the earthquake bush had dispatched 
transportation secretary samuel skinner to san francisco and 
directed vice president dan quayle in san diego after a speech to 
hook up with skinner for a helicopter inspection tour they were in 
touch during the day by telephone with bush 
fitzwater acknowledged the relief efforts for hurricane hugo 
could be strapped by the diversion of funds to the earthquake 
when the money runs out well have to assess the need and go 
back for more he said 
</TEXT>
