<DOCNO> AP891018-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
facts about the galileo spacecraft 
its probe and its mission 
orbiter 
height 15 feet 30 feet with antenna extended 
mass 5870 pounds 
payload 227 pounds 
instrument packages 11 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
probe 
height 34 inches 
mass 737 pounds 
payload 62 pounds 
instrument packages 6 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
schedule 
oct 18 1989 carried into earth orbit by the space shuttle 
atlantis 
feb 9 1990 galileo passes 9300 miles from venus where it 
will look for lightning and photograph the planets cloud 
circulation 
dec 8 1990 passes within 620 miles of earth examines 
composition of moons far side and maps earths atmospheric 
hydrogen 
oct 29 1991 caps 10month journey through the asteroid belt 
by passing within 600 miles of 10milewide asteroid gaspra 
examines geology and composition 
dec 8 1992 flies by earth a second time within 200 miles 
photographs moons north pole to determine if ice exists makes 
timelapse movie of earthmoon system 
aug 28 1993 second trip through asteroid belt comes within 
600 miles of 20milewide asteroid ida 
july 1995 probe separates from galileo orbiter to achieve 
better angle for later entry into jupiters atmosphere 
dec 7 1995 orbiter and probe arrive at jupiter with orbiter 
passing 620 miles from the moon io to brake it into orbit probe 
parachutes directly toward jupiters surface sending atmospheric 
data back to orbiter for 75 minutes before pressure destroys it 
december 1995 to october 1997 galileos orbiter continues 
circling jupiter relaying data to earth for 22 months it will 
receive aid from jupiters moon in shaping its wide orbits 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

