<DOCNO> AP891018-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
on the morning of april 18 1906 the people of san francisco 
woke abruptly to face calamity a devasting earthquake bringing 
widespread devastation and fire that killed at least 2500 and 
possibly 5000 people here are some excerpts of associated press 
accounts of that disaster 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
san francisco april 18 earthquakes and fire today have put 
nearly half of san francisco in ruins 
at least 200 persons have been killed thousands injured and 
the property loss will exceed 100000000 
thousands are homeless and destitute and all day long streams of 
people have been fleeing from the stricken districts to places of 
safety 
most of the principal buildings have already been destroyed and 
others are in imminent danger over all the scene of desolation 
hangs a dense pall of smoke 
it was 513 this morning when a terrific earthquake shock shook 
the whole city and surrounding country 
one shock apparently lasted two minutes and there was almost 
immediate collapse of flimsy structures all over the city 
the people became panicstricken and rushed into the streets 
most of them in their night attire they were met by showers of 
falling buildings bricks cornices and walls many were instantly 
crushed to death while others were dreadfully mangled 
fires have been raging all day and the fire department has been 
powerless to do anything except dynamite buildings threatened all 
day long explosions have shaken the city and added to the terror of 
the inhabitants 
all efforts to stay the progress of the fire were futile the 
south side of market street from ninth street to the bay was soon 
ablaze the fire covering a belt two blocks wide 
at the same time the commercial establishments and banks north 
of market street were burning the burning district in this section 
of the city extended from sansome street to the water front and 
the entire city seemed to be in flames 
the greatest destruction occurred in that part of the city which 
was reclaimed from san francisco bay much of the devasted district 
was at one time low marshy ground covered by water at high tide 
the damage by the earthquake to the residence portion of the 
city the finest part of which is on nob hill and pacific heights 
seems to have been slight 
the magnificent fairmount hotel not yet completed stands on 
the brink of nob hill overlooking the bay the hotel was not 
seriously damaged 
telegraph and telephone communication was shut off for a time 
the western union was put completely out of business and the 
postal company was the only company that managed to get a wire out 
of the city about 10 oclock even the postal was forced to 
suspend 
deep fissures opened in the filledin ground near the shore and 
the union ferry depot was injured 
the valencia hotel a fourstory wooden building sank into the 
basement a pile of splintered timbers under which were pinned 
many dead and dying occupants of the house the basement was full 
of water and some of the helpless victims were drowned 
at 9 oclock this morning 1000 men from the presido arrived 
down town to patrol the city streets the soldiers have been 
ordered to shoot down thieves caught in the act of robbng the dead 
and to guard with their lives the millions of dollars worth of 
property which has been placed in the streets that it may escape 
the ravages of the flames 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
scientists hope the galileo space 
probe carried into earth orbit aboard the space shuttle atlantis 
will find clues to the origin of the universe when it reaches 
jupiter in six years 
the mission also will look for organic chemicals in the gasses 
covering the largest planet chemicals that could also have been 
the basis for life on earth 
the jupiter system is so full of exciting phenomenon that we 
hardly know whats going on there said torrence johnson the 
galileo projects chief scientist what were trying to do is 
learn fundamental things about how the universe was formed how it 
ticks and where we came from 
the planet jupiter and its moons are in effect a minisolar 
system and jupiter itself is often called a star that never caught 
fire its hydrogenrich atmosphere should be a window into the 
conditions that existed when the sun and its planets formed 
the small probe will radio back readings during its 75minute 
plunge into the fifth planets atmosphere but galileo itself will 
continue a wide orbit around jupiter for 22 months keeping track 
of changes in its weather for the first longterm study of an outer 
planet 
while jupiter is the main target galileo will first circle 
venus to learn how its clouds circulate and look for lightning 
then the craft will fly twice by earth mapping hydrogen in the 
home planets atmosphere and photographing the moons north pole to 
look for ice 
galileo will also povide the first closeup data about 
asteroids passing within 600 miles of gaspra and ida on its way to 
jupiter 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891018-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
astronaut donald e williams a 
decorated navy captain who flew 330 combat missions in vietnam is 
commanding atlantis on its mission to deploy a nuclearpowered 
probe to jupiter 
williams 47 an astronaut for 11 years flew one previous 
shuttle mission as pilot of discovery in 1985 
williams said he looked forward to flying in space again its 
been quite a long time he said 
the lafayette ind native received a bachelors degree in 
mechanical engineering from purdue in 1964 he and his wife linda 
have two children jonathan 15 and barbara 13 
the mission is a very exciting one in my mind williams 
said were going to greatly increase the knowledge of humankind 
as a result of this mission 
characterizing his first shuttle flight as one of the 
highlights of his career williams added it also has been a 
longtime goal to command a mission 
williams wasnt sure he will be ready to hang up his flight suit 
after the atlantis mission 
id certainly like to fly again if that seems to be in the 
program he said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
navy cmdr michael j mcculley one 
of two space rookies assigned to the atlantis mission looked 
forward to gazing down at the earth while he was in orbit 
mcculley 46 the pilot of atlantis is making his first shuttle 
mission after being an astronaut for five years 
he was born in san diego calif but considers livingston 
tenn his hometown he earned his bachelors and masters degrees 
in metallurgical engineering from purdue university 
his wife jane is an amateur artist who helped design the 
flight patch for the atlantis crew mcculley has five children 
marla 20 marcy 17 cynthia 14 robyn 10 and sarah 3 
mcculley entered the navy as an enlisted man and served on one 
diesel and two nuclearpowered submarines he received his 
officers commission in 1970 
the thing that excites me the most about flying in space is 
to think about looking out and being able to see a round horizon 
being able to see much of the world he said 
when nasa officials told him he would be on the galileo mission 
mcculley said he was thrilled to be part of a project he can follow 
for years 
im so fortunate its incredible mcculley said in a recent 
interview i came out of high school when i was 17 years old and 
joined the navy and here i am 10 or 11 promotions later getting 
ready to go fly in space i have very few complaints about life 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
shannon lucid a mission specialist 
and veteran of one previous shuttle mission rode the shuttle into 
space wednesday to play a key role in the deployment of the galileo 
probe 
mrs lucid 46 had the job of checking galileos rocket 
booster the twostage rocket was to propel the probe out of earth 
orbit to start it on a sixyear journey to jupiter 
the biochemist flew one previous shuttle mission in 1985 
she was born in shanghai where her parents were missionaries 
just six weeks after her birth the family was taken prisoner by 
the japanese a year later they were released in a prisoner 
exchange 
she received her bachelors masters and doctorate degrees from 
the university of oklahoma and was selected as an astronaut in 1978 
when she was young she wanted to be an explorer but she thought 
there wouldnt be much left to explore by the time she grew up 
after reading science fiction and reports about work on a rocket 
she came to another conclusion 
i was thinking well shoot weve got the whole universe no 
one will have it all explored by the time i grow up so i thought 
thats what id like to be when i grew up of course the united 
states didnt have a space program at that time 
she and her husband michael have three children kawai 21 
shandara 19 and michael 14 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
mission specialist ellen s baker 
a physician and space rookie was sitting alone on the middeck 
during the shuttles blastoff wednesday 
once in orbit mrs baker 36 was responsible for checking the 
galileo space probe before deployment she and fellow astronaut 
franklin changdiaz also were designated to make a spacewalk if one 
was required 
she was born in fayetteville nc but her family later moved 
to new york city where her mother claire shulman is president of 
the borough of queens she earned a bachelors degree in geology 
from state university of new york at buffalo and received her 
doctorate in medicine from cornell 
she joined nasa in 1981 as a medical officer at the johnson 
space center 
she said she went to nasa to be a doctor but after three years 
decided she wanted to be an astronaut she was selected as an 
astronaut in 1984 
she and her husband kenneth have a 1yearold daughter karen 
mrs baker said it was difficult for her to believe she finally 
would be flying in space 
you work in a place so long and the time finally arrives 
she said it hasnt really clicked just yet 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
astronaut franklin changdiaz a 
physicist doubling as a mission specialist and flight engineer 
aboard atlantis has flown on one previous shuttle 
during the shuttles liftoff and landing his job was to monitor 
displays on the flight deck with the commander pilot and mission 
specialist shannon lucid 
changdiaz also was to help photograph the deployment of the 
galileo probe and he along with mission specialist ellen baker 
would participate in any unscheduled spacewalk 
changdiaz 39 a native of costa rica and a naturalized us 
citizen received his bachelors degree in mechanical engineering 
from the university of connecticut and a doctorate in applied 
plasma physics from the massachusetts institute of technology in 
1977 
changdiaz a visiting scientist at the massachusetts institute 
of technology became an astronaut in 1980 and made his first 
shuttle flight in 1986 aboard columbia 
he and his wife peggy have three children jean 15 sonia 
11 and lidia 1 
changdiaz said he also works on ways to help latin american 
countries get involved in space programs and hopes he can one day 
help establish an agency in the western hemisphere that is similar 
to the european space agency 
</TEXT>
