<TEXT>
abdou mohammed sold a cow in his egyptian 
village to to buy a bus ticket to libya where he hoped to make his 
fortune as a farmer 
today squatting beside the sidewalk stand where he sells 
plastic water bottles and combs he laments his decision 
i cant find any work he said all i want is just to 
go back home 
mohammed is among thousands of egyptians who in the last four 
months have poured across the border in search of prosperity in 
libya formerly egypts bitterest enemy their enticements are 
warmer official relations between the two countries and bleak 
prospects in egypt with its faltering economy 
wealth eludes most of them in libya however they compete with 
thousands of workers from south korea poland romania sudan and 
ghana for fewer jobs as reduced oil revenues force libya to abandon 
grandiose construction schemes 
many egyptians now arrive with made in egypt aluminum pots 
plastic mats and chocolate bars all libyan favorites 
but those like mohammed and his friend rabia ahmed brought 
only their visions of careers as farmers expecting to earn much 
more money than back home in sohag 245 miles south of cairo 
egypts capital 
there are no jobs so ive had to buy these from other 
egyptians said mohammed waving a hand over his wares lined up 
on the sidewalk of an old covered bazaar nearby other egyptians 
were selling similar items arrayed on similar cardboard sheets 
i sold my cow for 2000 pounds 780 mohammed said 
thats gone and now all i want is just to make enough for a 
return ticket and go back home he said 
however rabia ahmed who sold land to finance his move to 
libya said things could be worse than hawking egyptian 
paraphernalia to libyans 
i might continue the business he said 
life is not plush for egyptians newly arrived in benghazi the 
first major stop for buses on the routes across the border opened 
last summer for the first time in more than a decade 
scenes from cairos poor and squalid quarters have been 
transported to this mediterranean city egyptian women carrying 
babies roam among cars at traffic lights to beg others wipe 
windshields in hopes of earning a few dinars or sell plastic 
lanterns 
in september col moammar gadhafi the libyan leader came 
across hundreds of homeless egyptians in one of benghazis main 
parks shortly afterwards they were moved to an unfinished 
concreteandsteel school building 
all an egyptian needs to travel to libya is a 75pound 30 
work permit or an invitation 
when borders were reopened thousands of egyptians poured into 
libya many of them merchants along with them came skilled workers 
and farmers riding 20 buses and 250 private cars or taxis a day 
at salloum a border crossing on the egyptian side the few 
passport control and customs officers were unprepared for the 
traffic load one recent day 
it took seven hours for a bus with 53 passengers to pass through 
during the wait a passport officer said an average 1500 
egyptians go through every day by bus and car there were a lot 
more a month ago many have come back without jobs and in tears 
</TEXT>
