despite power outages that blacked out 
computers and shut down printing presses most newspapers in the 
san francisco bay area managed to publish wednesday copies were 
quickly snatched up by newshungry residents 
both the san francisco chronicle and the san francisco examiner 
published slimmeddown editions although there was no power at the 
headquarters and printing plant they share at fifth and mission 
streets 
hundreds dead in huge quake was the frontpage headline in 
the morning chronicle which had three white extras across the 
top on a black background 
the afternoon examiner had a headline reading 70 quake stuns 
bay a skyline over the masthead said earthquake extra 
the chronicle told its readers that it managed to print its 
16page special editions at its army street printing plant and an 
east bay facility near union city the first eight pages were 
devoted to earthquake coverage with the rest consisting of stories 
that had been set in type before the quake 
the chronicles news accounts were placed on macintosh computer 
discs using an emergency generator to power the computers 
the chronicle of oct 18 1989 is a newspaper produced with a 
heavy heart executive editor william german said in a frontpage 
statement the fact that it was produced at all was a mighty 
feat 
the tribune in oakland published wednesday morning as did the 
san jose mercury news a morning final edition of the mercury news 
included a special 12page earthquake section and a front page 
headline that read massive quake 150 die in seconds of horror 
it was not clear how many copies the newspapers were able to 
print 
