<TEXT>
beware of plays that include talking bears 
even if they are only part of a dream 
in beside herself which opened tuesday at offbroadways 
circle repertory company mary an aging lonely widow hears the 
voice of her longdead first love who happened to be her husbands 
brother he speaks through a furry creature that wanders into 
marys kitchen and sounds a little like james cagney with a head 
cold 
but the bear is just a fleeting vision conjured up by mary she 
has more extended visits from her past self as a young girl as a 
teenager and as a woman in her 20s you can tell they are from 
long ago because the smoke machine kicks in flooding the floor of 
marys island home with fog and the background music by jonathan 
brielle turns all tinkly 
playwright joe pintauro has written a memory play in which talk 
of the past nearly drowns the present and the audience what 
saves much of the evening is the fine acting of lois smith as mary 
and in a supporting role william hurt as a ups delivery man she 
tries to befriend 
they give a credibility to a play awash in symbolism and 
unconvincing dialogue between the woman and her other personas 
pintauro also has a fascination with wounded or dying animals a 
lot of the awkward conversation seems to return to the raccoons 
which keep getting hit on the highway next to marys house are 
they metaphorical standins for the poor woman 
theres a giddy vulnerability to smiths performance and she 
undergoes a remarkable physical transformation from dowdy old 
lady to understanding older woman between the plays two acts 
hurt returning as a member of the circle rep company for the 
first time in seven years plays against his blond good looks at 
first hes almost unrecognizable sporting long sideburns a fu 
manchu mustache and a baseball cap pulled down over his eyes and 
he affects a credible bluecollar accent that is a fine 
counterpoint to smiths more educated way of speaking 
their scenes together are warm and funny particularly when 
smith tries flirting with the younger man and he resists but not 
too hard melissa joan hart calista flockhart and susan bruce 
