in 1906 if tuesdays earthquake wasnt the big one it was 
close enough to send tremors of fear through natives used to the 
unsteady underpinnings of their city 
my first thought was it was the big one said gerald 
volkman who was drinking a milkshake at a groundfloor eatery when 
the quake struck 
the whole floor shook i was born and raised here and i never 
felt one like this i was scared 
the big one is the quake san franciscans have been told is 
just around the corner after every temblor of appreciable size 
newspapers radio and tv roll out stories about how the area could 
be devastated by a great quake and how to prepare for it 
every april on the anniversary of the 1906 quake and fire that 
killed at least 500 people here reporters interview survivors who 
recall that day when the earth heaved and the sky glowed with the 
flames of a city alight 
on tuesday smoke from a fire in the marina district near the 
bay rose high into the sky creating a backdrop to city hall miles 
away 
chuck gee also a native san franciscan thought he saw smoke 
from a fire as he jumped under a desk in his secondfloor office 
it was dust from masonry that fell into the street outside 
he said as he stood in front of a market street building whose 
broken sprinkler system sprayed water onto the busy thoroughfare 
im used to earthquakes ive even slept through some 
sometimes youre not sure if they are quakes and your first 
reaction is it might be a passing truck not this one i knew right 
away powerful thats what it was powerful 
gee spoke shortly after darkness set in only the lights of cars 
and other vehicles and the flashlights of a few pedestrians 
provided any light on market street 
people stood in clusters recalling their experiences their 
voices mingled with the sounds of pedestrians feet crushing 
splinters of glass the remains of windows that crashed to the 
pavement 
old buildings seemed to lose the most windows glass littered 
the front and sides of the old furniture mart on market street 
across the street the newer fox plaza apparently lost no windows 
further down market the san franciscan hotel lost some ornate 
facade fixtures 
one of the first rules of quake survival is to get in the clear 
and away from possible falling objects a lesson not lost on many 
who gathered in parking lots and in front of city hall 
another one might happen said roland hidalgo who stood in 
a parking lot off market he was asked what he did when the quake 
struck 
im religious he said i prayed 
down at powell and market people gathered around a 
batteryoperated radio to hear the latest news cable cars stood 
idle nearby 
sonia avitia of san jose asked for directions to a hotel she 
was told theyre all up and down powell street 
i want a new one she said i want an earthquakeproof 
one 
dora cortez said she wasnt too frightened during the quake 
cortez hands out religious tracts on market and she was very 
busy 
we are in the last days and things like earthquakes will 
happen she said 
people often ignore her and refuse to take the tracts 
not today yes yes she said 
</TEXT>
