<TEXT>
take a look at the potatoes in france if you 
want to learn something about the local lifestyle 
four years ago it was usual to see sacks of unwashed potatoes 
on supermarket shelves but such presentation is no longer 
acceptable says an agriculture department report 
today is is usual for raw potatoes sacked or loose to be 
washed before they are presented to shoppers the report said and 
many french food buyers are opting for frozen precooked potatoes 
the departments foreign agricultural service said the 
comingofage of frances baby boomers along with fewer 
adolescents and a rapid increase in senior citizens has meant a 
rise in demand for more conveniently packaged or prepared foods 
over twofifths of french women are now in the workforce 
the report said they want foods that require less preparation 
time stimulating a rise of readytoeat and microwaveable foods 
a similar trend developed in the united states in the 1970s and 
1980s the agency said in a forthcoming issue of agexporter 
magazine the study of french grocery habits was undertaken to help 
give us exporters a better understanding of the changing french 
market 
the increasing number of senior citizens also is creating a 
market for products and packaging adapted to the special needs of 
older consumers the report said 
and the leisurely french lunch is fading into memory as the 
typical french work week is becoming shorter the midday meal is 
more hurried increasing the demand for meals at fastfood 
restaurants and cafeterias 
more and more french consumers prefer to make a weekly trip to 
the supermarket rather than frequent and timeconsuming trips to 
butchers bakers produce markets and other small specialty 
shops the report said 
the preference for supermarket or hypermarket shopping is 
especially evident among singleperson and twoincome households 
where time for shopping is limited 
another result of the changes has been the domination of big 
supermarkets in the french retail grocery industry they accounted 
for 46 percent of grocery purchases in 1987 compared with 37 
percent in 1983 the report said 
this year for the first time french shoppers are estimated to 
buy more than 50 percent of their food in the big hypermarkets 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the agriculture department says private 
exporters have sold china additional us wheat under a price 
subsidy program 
f paul dickerson general sales manager for the departments 
foreign agricultural service said tuesday that three private 
exporting companies made the deals for a total of 300000 metric 
tons under the departments export enhancement program or eep 
the sales were part of 2 million tons authorized china under eep 
last feb 27 with the latest eep approvals china has 340000 tons 
remaining to be used under the current authorization 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels 
of wheat the latest sales would be about 11 million bushels at 
current prices estimated by usda at 385 per bushel the wheat 
would have a farm value of around 42 million 
under eep arrangements private exporters can sell us 
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in 
selected overseas markets and then collect free government 
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or subsidies 
dickerson said the latest subsidies averaged 1281 per ton or 
about 35 cents per bushel 
the subsidized sales were handled by the peavey co 210000 
tons cargill inc 50000 and bunge corp 40000 
with the latest sales china has bought about 43 million tons 
of us wheat for delivery in the 198990 marketing year that began 
on june 1 most of it without subsidies in 198889 china bought 
more than 8 million tons of us wheat all of it under the eep 
program 
