a replica of henry hudsons exploring ship 
the half moon left port on its first voyage four months late and 
towed by a tug boat 
the 85foot 120ton replica was pulled tuesday to new york 
city where it will enter a shipyard thursday for repairs on its 
diesel engine 
the replica of hudsons 17thcentury ship was originally 
scheduled to leave its berth july 5 for a tour of several ports 
but it was delayed in june by the death of the ships architect and 
chief builder nicholas benton who was killed when he fell from 
the mast of another ship 
engine problems further prolonged the departure of the ship 
interior work on the replica will be completed this winter in 
north carolina spokeswoman carole mcleod said 
the ship which cost about 1 million to build was conceived by 
andrew hendricks a north carolina resident who plans to use it to 
give lessons on the contributions of the dutch in us history 
