<TEXT>
making television sets that can decode closed 
captions for the hearing impaired would also benefit millions of 
other americans who need help with language and reading skills 
supporters say 
the captions can currently be seen only on televisions hooked up 
to a separate electronic decoder that costs about 180 limiting 
their availability 
but the national captioning institute on tuesday announced a 1 
million project to spur development of tvs with builtin decoders 
saying it would bring closedcaptioned programming to millions more 
americans with and without hearing problems 
tv sets with the decoder chip builtin will be attractive to 
people who find captioned television helpful in learning english 
said nci chairman warren h simmons jr were speaking of 
immigrants learning english as a second language as well as 
children who have reading problems 
the builtin decoder initially would add only about 20 to the 
cost of a television with costs eventually becoming negligible 
the institute predicted 
by the mid 90s we hope virtually all tv sets at least color 
tv midtolarge screen size models will be available with 
captioning as a welcomed new feature simmons said 
the institute a nonprofit corporation set up to provide 
closedcaptioned television service awarded itt corp a 1 million 
contract to design develop and produce the tiny decoder chip that 
could be built into new tvs vcrs and cable converters 
the grant was announced at gallaudet university the only 
accredited liberal arts college for the hearing impaired gallaudet 
president i king jordan said captioning expands the world for 
our deaf students its also valuable for many others such as the 
elderly experiencing hearing loss and those recently arrived in 
america and learning english 
i look forward to the day when captioning can be taken for 
granted as a right for all americans jordan said 
nci president john ball estimated the decoder chips could be 
available to tv manufacturers by late 1990 and that televisions 
equipped with the devices could be on the market by late 1991 or 
1992 
sharad rastogi director of marketing for itts semiconductor 
division said tv manufacturers see the builtin decoders as a 
attractive lowcost marketing feature and are anxious to 
incorporate the new technology 
closed captioning converts the audio portions of a television 
program into written words which are displayed on the television 
screen similar to the subtitles that appear on foreignlanguage 
films the captions can be switched on and off at the viewers 
option 
nearly 300 hours of closedcaptioned programming are available 
weekly on major networks and through cable services many 
videotapes also are captioned 
the national captioning institute said it plans to manufacture 
separate closedcaptioned decoders through the end of the century 
ball estimated about 250000 decoders are now in use he said the 
disadvantages of the separate decoder are its price and the 
complexity of hooking up another device to the tv in addition to 
vcrs and cable converters 
