<DOCNO> AP891018-0099 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a new drug that prevents and even reverses 
rejection of transplanted organs is 50 to 100 times more powerful 
than medication now used and is also less toxic a leading 
transplant surgeon said today 
its a marvelous drug said dr thomas e starzl of the 
university of pittsburgh who headed the team responsible for its 
development its the best drug that has been put out to this 
time 
the drug fk506 appears to be an eventual replacement for 
cyclosporine the major antirejection drug now being used he 
said it may also lower transplantation costs and prove useful in 
treating other disorders 
the biggest bonus is better survival starzl said in a 
telephone interview this morning 
dr robert corry president of the united network for organ 
sharing said he has not yet reviewed the findings but has every 
reason to believe that dr starzl is correct 
he certainly has made enormous contributions and this may be 
yet another one that hes done corry said 
starzl performed the worlds first liver transplant in 1963 and 
pioneered the use of cyclosporine in the early 1980s he first 
tried fk506 on a patient in february 
starzl and other university of pittsburgh doctors have since 
administered the drug to 111 patients including a few children 
the liver heart kidney pancreas and lung recipients were 
given fk506 after cyclosporine failed to work as intended or their 
transplanted organs had failed starzl said 
the new drug has been used on humans for only eight months 
making it difficult to predict the drugs longterm side effects 
starzl said so far though it has not caused kidney failure the 
leading side effect of cyclosporine 
researchers assume that fk506 like other antirejection drugs 
will increase patients risk of getting cancer that risk however 
probably will be not enough to cancel the effect and usefulness 
of this drug starzl said 
fk506 also has reduced the need for steroids normally 
administered with cyclosporine to help prevent rejection said 
starzl 
seventyfive to 80 percent of all patients receiving new livers 
in pittsburgh the worlds leading transplant center have properly 
functioning organs a year after surgery he said the success rate 
could climb to nearly 100 percent with fk506 he said 
starzl plans to present his findings later this month in 
barcelona spain 
a record 1680 liver transplants were performed in the united 
states among 12798 organ transplants last year according to the 
united network for organ sharing 
as of monday 18453 people were awaiting organ transplants in 
the united states the network said 
starzl said there is no reason for the time being for a patient 
to switch to fk506 if cyclosporine is not producing serious 
problems 
the new york times reported today that some scientists believe 
the apparent success of the drug derived from a fungus found in 
japan could worsen the already high shortage of donor organs 
because it would greatly increase the number of successful 
transplants 
starzl discounted that notion 
theoretically it should improve the donor supply in that 
people might be more accepting of transplantation with much better 
results corry said 
increased success rates mean fewer patients will require 
additional transplants starzl said twenty percent of pittsburghs 
liver transplant patients need another transplant within 60 days of 
surgery he said 
starzl said fk506 also will likely reduce the cost of liver 
transplants which exceeds 100000 by as much as onethird 
because of speedier recovery and less need for blood tests to 
monitor the drugs effectiveness 
starzls team plans wider use of the drug to treat disorders 
that impair the immune system and affect the skin eyes bowel 
kidney and brain the times said 
the university of pittsburgh is the only center with government 
approval to test the drug manufactured by fujisawa pharmaceutical 
company ltd of osaka japan 
dr gregory p burk of the food and drug administration told the 
times that the agency has encouraged starzl to submit patient 
records and other data for examination so it can determine whether 
to move quickly to allow other doctors to use the drug 
</TEXT>
