the senate sent president bush legislation 
today providing 18 million for pensions office costs and other 
expenses of the nations four living former presidents and lady 
bird johnson 
on a voice vote the senate gave final congressional approval to 
a spending bill containing the money there was no debate and only 
four senators were in the chamber when the measure passed 
the house approved the legislation tuesday on a 38330 vote 
under a 1958 law the government each year provides former 
presidents and their widows with pensions and money for their 
office space furnishings equipment staffs telephone mail and 
travel 
this year the legislation provides 559500 for ronald reagan 
387800 for jimmy carter 426800 for gerald ford 426700 for 
richard nixon and 22200 for the widow of lyndon johnson 
each presidents annual pension is 99500 their other expenses 
vary 
the figures do not include the costs of the secret service for 
protecting the former chief executives the secret service is 
expected to spend 125 million this year to provide security to 
the former presidents and their families 
there was no separate vote on the money for the former 
presidents but at one point rep paul kanjorski dpa complained 
about the costs singling out reagans plans to travel to japan 
shortly to reportedly deliver a pair of speeches for a 2 million 
fee he said it was an unmitigated atrocity for reagan to make 
such a trip with the help of taxpayers money 
this congress should examine whether we are too great in our 
largesse in providing services and costs to former presidents who 
engage in personal income endeavors he said 
the money was included in an 184 billion spending bill for the 
treasury department postal service and several smaller agencies 
for fiscal 1990 which began oct 1 
other parts of the bill provide 
200000 to renovate rooms in the vice presidents formal 
residence to accomodate the young family of dan quayle the quayle 
family had said they would raise money privately to pay for the 
work 
a 36 percent pay raise for all federal civilian employees 
