<TEXT>
parliament today overwhelmingly 
approved constitutional amendments that are to transform communist 
hungary into a multiparty democracy 
among the 94 changes passed by the 380member parliament were 
amendments eliminating all references to the leading role of the 
newly dissolved communist party justice minister kalman kulcsar 
said they effectively end oneparty rule in the east bloc nation 
the countrys formal name also was changed from peoples 
republic of hungary to republic of hungary to reflect a break with 
the communist past 
another change in the 1949 constitution abolishes the 21person 
collective presidency and replaces it with the office of the 
president 
the powers of president who also is commanderinchief of the 
armed forces and wields other authority will be temporarily 
assumed by parliament speaker matyas szueros until democratic 
elections are held next year 
one amendment states that political parties may be freely 
established and may freely function providing that they respect the 
constitution and the laws 
another declares that the leading role of the marxistleninist 
party of the working class has been outdated instead the 
necessary legal framework of a multiparty system must be stated 
the historic voting came on the heels of another landmark 
decision the dissolution last week of the communist party and its 
replacement by the hungarian socialist party 
unlike its monolithic marxistleninist predecessor the new 
party created last week professes commitment to multiparty 
democracy and market forces in the economy 
the moves are the latest in hungarys dizzying moves in the past 
year to break with its socialist past by establishing democratic 
economic and social reforms and improve ties to the west like 
poland hungarys rush to reform has created friction with 
hardline warsaw pact allies 
oneparty rule continues at least temporarily despite 
termination of the communist party its successor continues to 
dominate politics pending the nations first national multiparty 
elections in 41 years 
todays session also revealed differences on a key aspect of the 
countrys democratic strivings when and how to choose the 
nations president 
the government wants the election this year but opposition 
parties seek a postponement asserting they have no time or 
resources to organize against socialist party candidate imre 
pozsgay 
the opposition league of free democrats called for a plebiscite 
on a postponement and they want parliament to elect the president 
after a new legislature is chosen 
legislators today overwhelmingly approved a suggestion by 
premier miklos nemeth that parliament should not put the referendum 
issue to the vote but that separate committees deal with the topic 
later 
parliamentary elections to be scheduled by june would be the 
first instance of free multiparty voting on the national level 
since the communists consolidated power in 1948 
</TEXT>
