<DOCNO> AP891018-0184 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a new drug believed 50 to 100 times more 
powerful in preventing organ rejection might cut transplant costs 
and ease critical shortages of donor organs doctors said wednesday 
the biggest bonus is better survival said dr thomas e 
starzl head of the university of pittsburghs transplant program 
starzl heads the worlds only clinical trials of the japanese 
drug fk506 as of wednesday 111 transplant patients had received 
the experimental medication including a few children 
fk506 is far more effective and safer than cyclosporine the 
major antirejection drug now being used starzl said he estimated 
it to be 50 to 100 times more potent 
although we are idolaters of cyclosporine and have been in 
fact one of the prime developers of cyclosporine weve always 
realized its limitations practically from week two onward starzl 
said at a news conference 
theres a prospect now of doing things that couldnt be done 
previously such as intestinal transplants and ultimately 
crossspecies transplants starzl said 
the new drug shows promise in treating certain liver diseases 
thus eliminating the need for a transplant said dr david van 
thiel medical director of transplantation at the university of 
pittsburgh it also holds promise for treating rheumatoid 
arthritis multiple sclerosis and other disorders impairing the 
immune system 
dr robert corry president of the united network for organ 
sharing said he has not yet reviewed the findings but has every 
reason to believe that dr starzl is correct 
the drugs potential became apparent within only eight months of 
use on humans 
were shocked by it because it went so fast it was like 
throwing a gasoline bomb said starzl who will report his 
findings in an upcoming edition of the british medical journal 
lancet and at a scientific meeting oct 31 in spain 
starzl performed the worlds first liver transplant in 1963 and 
pioneered the use of cyclosporine in the early 1980s he first 
tried fk506 on a patient in february 
of the 111 patients 102 have been liver recipients said dr 
john fung a starzl colleague the rest have been heart kidney 
pancreas and lung recipients 
with cyclosporine the oneyear success rate of liver 
transplants has been 75 percent to 80 percent a rate that could 
rise to nearly 100 percent with fk506 starzl said the new drug 
also might lessen the need for two or more transplants in a single 
patient freeing organs for other recipients 
it really wasnt much of a decision to try fk506 said 
henry weber 37 of watertown ny one of the patients who used 
the drug i knew what the effects of cyclosporine were for the 
long run 
of the approximately 40 patients who started immediately on 
fk506 without having received cyclosporine none needed a second 
transplant or had kidney failure a leading side effect of 
cyclosporine 
fk506 could reduce the cost of a liver transplant which now 
exceeds 200000 by more than onethird because of speedier 
recovery and less need for blood tests to monitor the drugs 
effectiveness 
theoretically it should improve the donor supply in that 
people might be more accepting of transplantation with much better 
results corry said 
as of monday 18453 people were awaiting organ transplants in 
the united states the network said there were 12798 organ 
transplants performed in the nation last year 
researchers assume fk506 like other antirejection drugs will 
increase patients risk of getting cancer that risk however 
probably will not be enough to cancel the effect and usefulness 
of this drug starzl said 
while fk506 causes nausea stomach pains and headaches during 
the first few days when the drug is administered intravenously 
those side effects virtually disappear once oral treatment begins 
most patients take the drug daily but a few need it just once 
every three days and one person only once a week most 
antirejection drugs must be taken for life 
the us food and drug administration wants to consider the drug 
further before determining whether to allow wider use of it 
fk506 derived from a fungus found in japan is made by fujisawa 
pharmaceutical co ltd of osaka 
starzl is cautious about proceeding too quickly 
our fear is weve been so close to the drug and fueled by 
hope he said we dont want to be snowballed into this 
