the center for population options on wednesday 
called for massive public education and prevention programs to stem 
the rapid spread of aids among teenagers 
the center said schools churches community organizations and 
parents must do a better job correcting misinformation about aids 
helping teenagers delay sexual intercourse ensuring that those 
who do have sex use condoms and warning teenagers about the 
dangers of drug use 
our children have a right to straightforward accurate 
information about hiv infection and how to prevent it said a 
report issued by the nonprofit educational center and partially 
funded by the centers for disease control 
the number of aids cases among teenagers jumped by 43 percent 
to 398 between july 1988 and july 1989 according to the cdc 
but because the time between infection and the onset of aids can 
be as long as 10 years public health officials believe that many 
people with aids who are now in their 20s may have picked up the 
virus when they were teenagers 
the report also says cdcs figures also show that a greater 
proportion of adolescents than adults with aids is female 19 
percent for teenagers compared with 9 percent among adults 
wanda wigfallwilliams director of the centers aids programs 
said the figures show that the projected spread of the virus among 
heterosexuals is becoming a reality among adolescents 
the centers report says hiv programs should vary in content and 
format depending on the audience intended to be reached but each 
program should emphasize certain basic information including how 
the human immunodeficiency virus or hiv is transmitted how it is 
not transmitted and how to protect against infection including 
abstaining from sexual intercourse and use of condoms by those who 
do have sex 
but the report advises simply providing young people with 
facts is not enough correct and precise language should be used 
to describe everything from risky sexual practices to proper use of 
condoms the report said 
the report also suggests that health clinics make condoms 
available to young people and that hiv prevention programs 
encourage effective condom use by getting teenagers comfortable 
talking about and buying condoms 
the report emphasizing the risk of aids to teenagers cites 
studies showing that teenagers on average begin sexual intercourse 
at about age 16 and that each year one in six teenagers contracts 
a sexuallytransmitted disease and more than 1 million teenage 
girls become pregnant 
drug and alcohol use is also implicated in the spread because 
they make it less likely a young person will protect themselves 
during sex and through addiction often lead to sex in exchange 
for money or drugs the report said 
