<TEXT>
aftershocks to tuesdays killer quake 
shook the battered san francisco bay area today as work crews gave 
up hope of finding anyone alive beneath a wrecked freeway and 
stunned californians struggled to put order back in their lives 
at least 272 people were reported killed and 1400 injured in 
the catastrophic earthquake which in 15 seconds wrecked buildings 
across nearly 100 miles a section of the bay bridge and at least 
two spans near santa cruz fell and electric power was cut for as 
many as 1 million residents 
severed gas lines touched off fires including one in san 
francisco that burned a block of buildings but all the blazes were 
out or under control today 
extensive damage was reported in parts of santa cruz and san 
benito counties 70 miles to the south which were closest to the 
epicenter of the earthquake 
the quake 69 on the richter scale was the seconddeadliest in 
us history surpassed only by the great san francisco earthquake 
of 1906 when 2500 or more were killed 
the magnitude of the disaster emerged slowly today as officials 
made contact with hardhit areas outlying suburbs and towns where 
many telephones were cut off 
the devastation is just horrible said gov george 
deukmejian who cut short a trade mission to west germany lt gov 
leo mccarthy said damage would total the better part of 1 
billion 
san francisco mayor art agnos urged commuters to stay home 
rather than tax the transportation system crippled by the closing 
of the bay bridge but as dawn spread over the glassstrewn streets 
of the region people tried to revive a sense of normalcy some 
making their way to work by ferry by foot or over highways not 
blocked by damage the bay area rapid transit system reopened this 
morning as did the oakland and san francisco airports 
many people stayed home however their workplaces shut down in 
the quakes aftermath most schools and many other institutions 
were closed as well 
san franciscos financial district was unusually quiet the 
