<DOCNO> AP891018-0201 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the cold fusion laboratory reaction is a 
mystery that unmistakably produces heat and merits more research 
though it is unlikely ever to be a useful energy source scientists 
said wednesday 
john appleby of texas aampm and paul c w chu of the university 
of houston cochairmen of closed conference on cold fusion said 
some new unpublished experiments discussed in private by about 50 
scientists showed that the cold fusion apparatus developed at the 
university of utah can show an unexplained production of heat 
but it still is unclear if the reaction is chemical nuclear or 
some previously unrecognized phenomenon 
we are happy our results are showing that something strange is 
going on said appleby 
he added that there is no evidence that the process would 
ever be useful in energy devices based on present very limited 
knowledge 
the conference sponsors the national science foundation and the 
electric power research institute originally did not plan to 
announce any conclusions but in response to requests from 
reporters chu appleby and three other scientists held a news 
conference 
appleby and chu both both declined to give details of new cold 
fusion experiments conducted by researchers attending the meeting 
because the results have not been published 
but in a prepared statement chu said that new positive 
results in excess heat production and nuclear product generation 
have been presented and reviewed 
based on the information that we have these effects cannot be 
explained as a result of artifacts equipment error or human 
error said chu however he said there are problems in the 
predictable reproduction of the effects and in relating these 
effects to known reactions 
among those attending the conference were stanley pons and 
martin fleischmann the two scientists who first claimed to have 
achieved cold fusion in test tube experiments at the university 
of utah where pons is a chemistry professor fleischmann is on the 
faculty of the university of southampton in the united kingdom 
pons and fleischmann stunned fusion researchers last march when 
they announced at a news conference that they had achieved cold 
fusion with a device composed of a electrodes of platinum and 
palladium immersed in a flask of deuterium oxide or heavy water 
they claimed that electricity applied to the water forced deuterium 
atoms into the crystal lattice of the palladium 
the deuterium atoms in the metal they said eventually became 
so dense that some fused giving off heat equal to four times the 
energy put in 
deuterium is a form of hydrogen the fusion reaction in which 
hydrogen atoms merge to form helium and liberate energy is what 
powers all stars and thermonuclear weapons 
normally an extremely energetic trigger an atomic bomb for a 
thermonuclear weapon collapsing clouds of interstellar gas for 
stars is needed to ignite fusion billions of dollars have been 
spent in the last 40 years trying to find a way to harness fusion 
reactions as practical energy sources that would liberate more 
energy than they consume 
up to now most scientists have dismissed the utah findings as 
somehow erroneous 
appleby said new data from pons and fleischmann and from other 
researchers has rehabilitated the reputation of the utah 
research few scientists however believe the reaction is actually 
fusion 
it is an anomalous phenomeon which cannot be black magic but 
cannot be explained by the normal rules of chemistry said chu 
edward teller a prominent nuclear physicist who helped develop 
the first atomic bomb and pushed development of the first 
thermonuclear weapons attended the cold fusion workshop in a 
statement read at the news conference teller said many cold fusion 
results are in disagreement with the solidly established nuclear 
theory of fusion and urged more research 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

