a group of educators has decided to 
publish the american equivalent of a soviet math and physics 
magazine to counter what they say is the poor state of high school 
education in the united states 
the magazine called quantum will be aimed at gifted high 
school students organizers at harvard university said it will 
begin by publishing material translated from the original soviet 
magazine kvant but may eventually expand to include articles by 
american scientists 
kvants articles are written by leading soviet scientists and 
address current issues in math and physics and include sets of 
problems for students to solve 
sheldon glashow a nobel laureate and professor of physics at 
harvard will serve as quantums physics editor 
glashow said he hopes the magazine will improve american science 
education 
he said test results have placed us students at a level of 
general science knowledge roughly equivalent to that of 
underdeveloped countries 
american math education is in terrible shape added william 
thurston a faculty member at princeton university who will be 
quantums math editor 
the first copies of quantum will be distributed in november the 
magazines organizers said they have received a grant from the 
national science foundation and plan to support the publication 
through advertising and subscriptions 
there will be 100000 copies printed for the first issue nine 
issues will be published per year 
