<TEXT>
workers on wall street are earning more money 
than ever if theyre still working 
a federal report tuesday said 15000 securities industry 
employees here have lost their jobs since the stock market crash of 
october 1987 for those who survived however average pay was 
nearly 79000 last year 
that was a 13 percent salary increase over 1987 and it came to 
more than 25 times the average annual pay for all private 
employees in new york city 
the report by the regional bureau of labor statistics said new 
yorks economy was not devastated by the 1987 crash as some 
feared but employment has been essentially flat since the crash 
after a decade of growth 
the postcrash record has clearly not been the disaster widely 
touted by the forecasts and in the headlines in the early months 
following black monday the report said but it does close out 
a period of unprecedented private sector job expansion marking a 
distinct break with the past 
samuel ehrenhalt regional commissioner of labor statistics 
said the stock markets more recent gyrations were part of an 
ongoing restructuring in the securities industry 
the stock market crash two years ago marked the end of the 
resurgence of the 80s and the beginning of a transition thats 
still taking shape said ehrenhalt what youre seeing now is a 
continuation of structural changes on wall street that process 
hasnt reached its end point 
at the same time wall streets rising salaries indicated a 
good deal of vitality ehrenhalt said average annual pay in the 
securities industry in the city has risen from 19317 in 1975 to 
78625 last year 
the figures indicated that securities workers laid off since the 
crash were the least productive and lowest paid ehrenhalt said 
the securities industry in new york now employs 146000 people 
down from a peak of 163000 in december 1987 hiring momentum 
carried it to its peak two months after the crash of oct 19 1987 
before the crash wall street employment had increased by an 
average of 12000 jobs a year since the early 1980s 
the banking industry also lost jobs as a result of the 1987 
market crash with employment falling by 9500 in the past two 
years the agency said banking jobs had been declining before the 
crash but far more slowly 
