<TEXT>
top officials of the nations four largest 
futures exchanges told a senate committee that some proposed market 
reforms could drive their business overseas 
at the same hearing tuesday the head of the agency that 
oversees the futures markets said the proposed legislation gives 
the markets more power than they want 
wendy l gramm chairwoman of the commodity futures trading 
commission said her agency neither needs nor wants authority to 
conduct undercover operations like the one that resulted in 46 
indictments this summer in chicagos freewheeling commodities 
trading pits 
i believe the current situation with the fbi having the 
authority is sufficient ms gramm told the senate agriculture 
nutrition and forestry committee which is considering legislation 
to reform the futures markets and reauthorize financing for the 
cftc which oversees them 
ms gramm also said 
she believed that 17 of the indicted chicago traders still were 
working in the pits including some handling customer orders she 
expressed concern about it but said the regulatory agency had to 
balance that against the rights of the accused theyre indicted 
they havent been tried and convicted 
temporary trading halts known as circuit breakers and 
other market safeguards implemented since the 1987 stock market 
crash appeared to work as designed during fridays stock market 
plunge she also said she was satisfied with intermarket 
communication during the stock slide 
there was no need to give the cftc power to order crooked 
brokers to pay restitution to customers they have cheated a 
majority of the commission believes current law provides sufficient 
recourse for customers to obtain reimbursement of losses when funds 
are available she said 
at the same hearing officials of the chicago board of trade 
the chicago mercantile exchange the new york mercantile exchange 
and the new yorkbased commodity exchange warned senators that 
tougher recordkeeping standards and service fees mandated by the 
bill could make them uncompetitive with foreign markets 
in addition to undercover probes and broker restitution the 
proposed futures trading practices act of 1989 would require 
stricter recordkeeping by market participants to independently 
precisely and completely record transaction times 
at issue is the audit trail an accurate record of any given 
transaction that would allow investigators to determine if it 
reflected what really happened and if the transaction followed the 
rules 
the general accounting office the investigatory arm of the 
congress has found that current recordkeeping on most exchanges 
is inadequate to prevent fraud because so much of it is orginated 
by traders themselves often by hand 
the bill also calls for financing steppedup floor surveillance 
through service fees which several exchanges have criticized as a 
secret tax 
the worst outcome of this reauthorization process said bot 
chairman karsten mahlmann would be to use the chicago indictments 
as an excuse for imposing audit trail standards utterly 
incompatible with a liquid market or raising costs of access to our 
customers by imposing new and unwarranted taxes on our markets 
he added that new fees could constitute a crushing burden and 
competitive handicap against foreign markets that arent as 
restricted 
the bill is sponsored by sen patrick leahy dvt the 
committee chairman and sen richard g lugar of indiana the 
panels ranking republican 
futures contracts are agreements to deliver a quantity of goods 
at a specified price at a certain time in the future they are used 
by producers of such commodities as soybeans or gold to lock in a 
favorable price while speculators buy and sell those contracts in 
pursuit of a profit 
during this past year said leahy regulation of the 
futures industry has lurched from crisis to crisis 
in addition to the undercover fbi probe that resulted in the 
chicago indictments a separate probe of futures exchanges in new 
york was disclosed in may 
in july the cbot issued an emergency order requiring traders to 
slash their holdings in soybeans futures contracts the order 
touched off wild fluctuations in soybean prices 
a bill also containing futures market reform was passed by the 
house last month both bills seek to limit dual trading the 
controversial but legal practice that allows traders to conduct 
transactions for their own accounts as well as those of their 
customers 
ms gramm said a study by her agency found dual trading does not 
have the impact on futures markets that its supporters have claimed 
